    <title>Combined summary - Finite monetary supply for Bitcoin</title>
    <updated>2023-06-08T18:15:53.224089+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2014-April/004964.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In April 2014, Pieter Wuille proposed the idea of turning Bitcoin into a limited-supply currency and wrote a draft BIP for discussion. He believed that the current subsidy schedule was unacceptable and suggested reducing the block reward by half every four years until it reaches zero, which would result in a maximum supply of 21 million Bitcoins. Matt Corallo suggested redesigning the whole system with a hard fork instead of a soft fork, but questioned whether the community could reach an agreement in such a short timeframe. The proposal was met with controversy, but Wuille considered it a worthwhile idea to explore. In an email exchange on April 5, 2014, Matt Whitlock and Jorge Timón discussed their preferences for date formats. Timón expressed his liking for both DD-MM-YYYY and YYYY-MM-DD formats but disliking MM-DD-YYYY and YYYY-DD-MM. Whitlock pointed out that Timón's preferences reflect a cultural bias and argued that the only entirely numeric date format that is unambiguous across all cultures is YYYY-MM-DD. He also noted that no culture uses YYYY-DD-MM, or at least the ISO seems to think so.Several email exchanges between Bitcoin developers were discussed. In one conversation, Luke-Jr proposed a controversial idea to turn Bitcoin into a limited-supply currency. Pieter Wuille responded skeptically, but Benjamin Cordes recommended a book about mathematical music theory called Topos of Music, which he believed could have applications to Bitcoin. In another email exchange, Matt Whitlock pointed out that the creation date in the BIP header has the wrong format and should be 01-04-2014 as per BIP 1. The use of date formats in BIPs was also discussed, and frustration was expressed with the choice of format used in RFC 822, which predates ISO 8601 by half a decade. Additionally, there was a discussion about a bug in Bitcoin's network that could cause an economic shock if not addressed properly, and a solution proposed by Peter Todd involved implementing the OP_CHECKLOCKTIMEVERIFY opcode in a soft-fork, followed by another soft-fork requiring miners to "pay-forward" a percentage of their coinbase outputs to the future. Finally, the topic of date formats was discussed, and it was pointed out that the only entirely numeric date format that is unambiguous across all cultures is YYYY-MM-DD according to the International Organization for Standardization (ISO). Gregory Maxwell assigned BIP 42 to a proposal after receiving a "rather large bribe" on April 1, 2014. There were ten people commenting on the proposal and consensus seemed unlikely. Luke-Jr proposed a controversial idea to turn Bitcoin into a limited-supply currency on April 1, 2014. Pieter Wuille responded skeptically to the proposal, but Luke-Jr remained enthusiastic, linking to a cleaned-up version of the proposal and suggesting that tonal numbers would be used in Bitcoin by the year 2214. Benjamin Cordes also joined the conversation, recommending a book about mathematical music theory called Topos of Music, which he believed could have applications to Bitcoin.</summary>
